    {"id": "r001", "domain": "reasoning", "question": "Why does NeuroRAG use hybrid retrieval instead of dense-only?",
     "answer": "Hybrid retrieval combines BM25 keyword matching with FAISS semantic search. Dense-only retrieval misses exact term matches; sparse-only lacks semantic understanding. RRF fusion produces higher recall and robustness than either method alone."},
    {"id": "r002", "domain": "reasoning", "question": "Why is the circuit breaker pattern necessary in production RAG?",
     "answer": "Without a circuit breaker, repeated LLM failures cause cascading delays as each request waits for timeout. The circuit breaker detects sustained failures and fails fast, protecting from resource exhaustion and improving perceived latency during outages."},
    {"id": "r003", "domain": "reasoning", "question": "Why is RRF preferred over score normalisation for hybrid fusion?",
     "answer": "Score normalisation requires understanding score distributions which vary per query and dataset. RRF uses only rank positions, making it invariant to score magnitude differences and effective without tuning."},
    {"id": "r004", "domain": "reasoning", "question": "Why is faithfulness more important than fluency for RAG evaluation?",
     "answer": "A fluent answer can still hallucinate unsupported facts. Faithfulness measures whether every claim is grounded in retrieved context, directly quantifying hallucination risk. A faithful but clumsy answer is safer than a fluent but inaccurate one."},
    {"id": "r005", "domain": "reasoning", "question": "Why does the self-healing loop use a confidence threshold instead of fixed iterations?",
     "answer": "Fixed iterations waste compute on easy queries and may be insufficient for hard ones. A threshold stops iteration when quality is sufficient, balancing latency and quality dynamically per query."},
    {"id": "r006", "domain": "reasoning", "question": "Why is the cross-encoder reranker applied after initial retrieval rather than as the primary retriever?",
     "answer": "Cross-encoders cannot pre-compute document representations, making them too slow to score every document in the corpus. The fast retriever prunes to a shortlist; the reranker applies expensive scoring only to that shortlist."},
    {"id": "r007", "domain": "reasoning", "question": "Why does semantic chunking outperform fixed-size chunking?",
     "answer": "Fixed-size chunking splits semantically coherent passages arbitrarily, producing context-deficient chunks. Semantic chunking respects topic boundaries, ensuring each chunk contains complete, interpretable information."},
    {"id": "r008", "domain": "reasoning", "question": "Why is a canary deployment preferable to direct full rollout for LLM updates?",
     "answer": "LLM updates can subtly degrade answer quality not caught by automated tests. A canary routes small traffic to the new version for real-world monitoring. Issues affect only the canary fraction and rollback is fast."},
